A small fire started in dry underbrush because a hiker left a cigarette. The children had planted healthy trees, so the fire could not spread easily. Rangers came fast and stopped the fire before it grew.  
The feeling said, “Danger, fire.”  
After that season, when the wind blew through the redwoods, villagers said they could almost hear the trees sing.  
In the shadow of an ancient redwood forest lived Mira. She could hear trees speak, not in words but in slow, deep feelings that came through her bare feet on mossy paths.  
Later, Mira sat with Grandfather Cedar. The feeling was gratitude, warm and slow like sunlight through leaves.  
Mira returned to Grandfather Cedar. The feeling grew stronger. She sat under him for three days, listening. On the fourth day she understood: the danger was not a wildfire, but rot inside the trees. Beetles carried the sickness through the roots.  
She gathered village children. Together they collected sap from healthy trees, mixed it with herbs the elders knew, and painted the mixture on the trunks near Grandfather Cedar. It was a desperate, hopeful gesture.  
She leaned on him and whispered, “We heard you.”  
She ran to the ranger station and said, “The forest is afraid. There will be a fire.”  
The forest answered in the rustle of a thousand branches, a sound like breathing, like thanks.  
Grandfather Cedar was over a thousand years old. His voice was the slowest of all, a low vibration that took days to form a single thought. One spring, Mira pressed her palm to his rough bark and felt something urgent.  
The rangers smiled kindly but said there had been no lightning or campfires left burning. “The season is wet,” they said. “Everything is safe.”  
Weeks passed. Summer came hot and dry. One morning Mira woke to smoke—thin and acrid. She ran to the forest.</p>